columns.text:
The future value is computed using the following formula:

$$\begin{align*}
\text{Future Value}=\text{Present Value}\cdot(1+\text{r})^\text{t}
\end{align*}$$

Increasing the length of time will result in a increase in the future value as well. As "t" (t equals the length of time) increases, so does the future value interest component (1+r) which is proportional to the increase in t. The reason for this is that  the amount accumulates interest for an additional period, increasing the future value of the amount.

The present value is computed using the following formula:

$$\begin{align*}
\text{Present Value}=\dfrac{\text{Future Value}}{(1+\text{r})^\text{t}}
\end{align*}$$

Increasing the length of time will result in a decrease in the present value. This is due to the fact that as "t" grows, the component of the present value of interest becomes smaller (t is equal to the length of time). As a result, the present value of the amount decreases.

*Case 1:*
$$ \begin{aligned}
FV_1 &= \$100\cdot(1+0.10)^ 1\\
&= \boxed{\$110}
\end{aligned}$$

*Case 2:*
$$ \begin{aligned}
FV_2 &= \$100\cdot(1+0.10)^ 2\\
&= \boxed{\$121}
\end{aligned}$$

The value in case 2 is bigger than the value of case 1 **($110<$121)**

*Case 1:*
$$ \begin{aligned}
PV_1 &= \frac{\$100}{(1+0.10)^1}\\
&= \boxed{\$90.91}
\end{aligned}$$

*Case 2:*
$$ \begin{aligned}
PV_2 &= \frac{\$100}{(1+0.10)^2}\\
&= \boxed{\$82.64}
\end{aligned}$$

The value in case 1 is bigger than the value of case 2 **($90.91>$82.64)**
